04373nam a22005175i 9780773562332DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19901990xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735623327 a10.1515/97807735623322doi  a(DE-B1597)655311  a(OCoLC)1394872256  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJL103.E8bH55 1990eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a354.710611 aHilliker, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCanada's Department of External Affairs, Volume 1 :bThe Early Years, 1909-1946 /cJohn Hilliker. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1990] 4c©1990  a1 online resource (440 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCanadian Public Administration Series ;v1600tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustrations -- tBeginnings: To 1926 -- tExternal Relations to 1909 -- tFoundation of the Department: 1909–1911 -- tEarly Operations: 1911–1921 -- tSkelton Takes Charge: 1921–1926 -- tThe Foreign Service: 1926–1939 -- tCreation of a Foreign Service: 1926–1930 -- tThe Foreign Service at Work: 1930–1935 -- tThe Foreign Service on the Rise: 1935–1939 -- tWar and Transition: 1939–1946 -- tAt War under Skelton: 1939–1941 -- tAdjusting to New Demands: 1941–1943 -- tPreparing for Victory: 1943–1945 -- tPlanning a New International Order: 1943–1946 -- tNote on Sources -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter an introductory chapter dealing with the conduct of external relations before 1909, the book examines three distinct phases of the department's development. Although the department had modest beginnings under the first under-secretary, Sir Joseph Pope (1909-1925), it was seen by his successor, O.D. Skelton, as an important instrument for the assertion of Canadian autonomy. Skelton presided over the establishment of the first Canadian diplomatic missions abroad, and was responsible for the creation of a foreign service to staff them. With the outbreak of the war in 1939, both the responsibilities and the size of the department underwent substantial organizational change under Norman Robertson, who became under-secretary after Skelton's death in 1941. Taken together, the criteria for recruitment introduced by Skelton and the reorganization which took place under Robertson gave the department many of the features which have characterized it as a branch of the Canadian government. The further development of the institution will be examined in a second volume covering the years 1946-1968. Since the prime minister was secretary of state for External Affairs during much of the period covered by volume I, the book contributes to an understanding of the operation of the Canadian government as a whole as well as of a single department. It also examines the policy making process and therefore will be of interest to students of international relations as well as of public administration.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356233240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773562332423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773562332/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles